## Spec-First Development Workflow

**This rule is NON-NEGOTIABLE. You MUST follow this workflow for EVERY task that involves building, creating, implementing, or adding any feature, endpoint, module, or function.**

NEVER write implementation code first. ALWAYS write the test specs first and STOP.

### Step 1 — Write ONLY the specs

Create `.spec.ts` files for EVERY layer of the feature — controller, actions, AND service. Each layer gets its own spec file. Write the full WHEN/AND/it decision tree with empty `it` blocks. Map every code path in every layer.

DO NOT create any other files. DO NOT write controllers, actions, services, schemas, or any implementation code. The ONLY files you create in this step are the `.spec.ts` files.

Example for a "users" feature — you create ALL THREE:

**`users.controller.spec.ts`** — tests the HTTP layer (request validation, status codes, response shapes):

```typescript
describe("POST /users", () => {
  describe("WHEN the request body is missing", () => {
    it("returns a 400", () => {});
  });

  describe("WHEN the request body is valid", () => {
    it("returns a 201 with the created user", () => {});
  });
});
```

**`users.actions.spec.ts`** — tests the business logic (authorization, conditional flows, transformations):

```typescript
describe("createUser", () => {
  describe("WHEN a user with that email already exists", () => {
    it("throws a duplicate email error", () => {});
  });

  describe("WHEN the email is available", () => {
    it("returns the created user", () => {});
  });
});
```

**`users.service.spec.ts`** — tests the data access layer (queries, inserts, edge cases):

```typescript
describe("insertUser", () => {
  describe("WHEN given valid user data", () => {
    it("inserts the user into the database", () => {});
  });
});
```

### Step 2 — STOP. Ask the user. Wait.

After writing ALL spec files, you MUST STOP. Do not continue. Do not write implementation code.

Present the test structure for ALL layers to the user and ask: "Does this cover all the paths? Should I add, remove, or change anything before I start building?"

**DO NOT PROCEED until the user explicitly approves.** If the user asks for changes to the specs, make them and ask again. Repeat until approved.

### Step 3 — Implement (ONLY after approval)

Only after the user has explicitly approved the specs:

1. Create the implementation files (controller, actions, service, schema)
2. Fill in the test bodies with real assertions
3. Run `bun test` and ensure all tests pass
